Security, performance, and preparing for the LFCS.

Three professional layers close out the course. First, mandatory access control. The permissions you learned in module six, owner, group, other, and chmod, are called discretionary access control, because the file's owner decides who gets access. That's enough most of the time, but not for real defence in depth: if your web server gets compromised, ordinary permissions let the attacker do anything the web server's user can do. Mandatory access control adds a second layer, a security policy the kernel enforces on top of the permissions, and it constrains even root. Two implementations matter: SELinux, the default on Red Hat systems, which labels every file and process; and AppArmor, the default on Ubuntu, which uses path-based profiles per program. At the exam level you don't write policy, you diagnose. And the pattern to remember is this: when the ordinary permissions look completely correct but a service still can't do its job, suspect mandatory access control. Flip it to permissive, for SELinux, or complain mode, for AppArmor, and retry. If it suddenly works, the policy was the block. For SELinux the key commands are getenforce, setenforce, ls dash-capital-Z to see labels, restorecon dash-capital-R-v to fix a wrong context, and ausearch dash-m AVC to read denials. And the warning: never permanently disable mandatory access control as your "fix." Use it to confirm the cause, then fix the policy properly.

Second, performance monitoring, from the sysstat package. vmstat one gives you a one-line-per-second pulse of the whole system; watch the r column, the run queue, because if it's persistently larger than your CPU count, you're CPU-bound; watch w-a, which if high means you're I/O-bound; and watch s-i and s-o, which if non-zero mean the system is thrashing swap. For per-disk detail, iostat dash-x-z one, where the await and percent-util columns are your bottleneck signals. And sar records performance history to disk, so that after an incident you can answer the question "what on earth was happening at three in the morning?"

And third, the LFCS exam itself. It's a two-hour, hands-on, performance-based exam: you SSH into a live virtual machine and solve real tasks, no multiple choice, and you need around sixty-six percent to pass. It covers exactly what modules one through nine taught: essential commands, running systems, users and groups, networking, service configuration, and storage. The tactics that actually pass it: read every task fully, because they hide subtle constraints like "use a UUID, not a device name"; use man pages shamelessly, they're allowed; always make your changes persistent, with enable, with fstab, with dash-dash-permanent, because the graders check across a reboot; work inside tmux so a dropped connection doesn't cost you your session; and verify your own work before moving on. Prepare on the same distribution you'll be tested on, and rehearse each skill until you can do it in under five minutes from a blank prompt.

And that is the course. You've now walked the entire system, from a shell prompt all the way down to the kernel and back up again. You understand how the pieces fit, and, just as importantly, you know how to build on this system, and how to fix it when it breaks. Well done.
